I... can't go back to the future...

278
00:13:51,230 --> 00:13:52,450
I... can't go back to the future...

279
00:13:54,500 --> 00:13:56,400
In other words,
this is what's going on.

280
00:13:56,960 --> 00:14:00,700
We are going through an eternal loop
of the same time period.

281
00:14:04,770 --> 00:14:08,400
Even if you can say something as impossible
as that with a smile on your face...

282
00:14:08,540 --> 00:14:11,740
Koizumi, do you realize
what you're saying?

283
00:14:11,850 --> 00:14:15,480
I do. Much more than
I wish I did.

284
00:14:15,620 --> 00:14:18,350
I had just been speaking
with Miss Asahina.

285
00:14:18,490 --> 00:14:21,220
Call me too, when you
have talks with her.

286
00:14:21,320 --> 00:14:24,350
And as a result, what we realized
was that recently,

287
00:14:24,490 --> 00:14:26,720
the flow of time
was a bit strange.

288
00:14:27,530 --> 00:14:30,500
You might want to credit this
to Miss Asahina.

289
00:14:30,800 --> 00:14:33,460
Thanks to her,
I was able to confirm it.

290
00:14:34,270 --> 00:14:35,860
Confirm what?

291
00:14:36,000 --> 00:14:40,030
That we have experienced the same
span of time numerous times.

292
00:14:40,170 --> 00:14:41,610
You said that earlier.

293
00:14:42,280 --> 00:14:47,370
To be precise, we've been repeating
the time from August 17th to the 31 st.

294
00:14:47,510 --> 00:14:51,380
We're in the middle of an
endless summer vacation.

295
00:14:51,520 --> 00:14:54,350
Well, it is
summer vacation, but...

296
00:14:54,560 --> 00:14:57,420
It's a never-ending
endless summer.

297
00:14:57,560 --> 00:15:02,090
This world has lost all time
after September 1 st.

298
00:15:02,630 --> 00:15:06,160
That is why Miss Asahina
cannot go back to the future.

299
00:15:06,330 --> 00:15:08,600
I suppose you could say
that it's natural.

300
00:15:09,600 --> 00:15:12,570
What's natural about there
being no future?

301
00:15:12,710 --> 00:15:14,770
Who'd believe it?

302
00:15:16,980 --> 00:15:20,850
We'd like for you to believe it,
at the very least.

303
00:15:21,120 --> 00:15:25,680
Are we trapped inside one of
those closed spaces?

304
00:15:25,820 --> 00:15:27,790
No, that's not it.

305
00:15:27,920 --> 00:15:31,120
A single portion of time
has been torn away.

306
00:15:31,430 --> 00:15:35,160
At exactly the point when it becomes
midnight on August 31 st,

307
00:15:35,300 --> 00:15:39,530
everything resets, and we go back
to August 17th. That's the process.

308
00:15:40,230 --> 00:15:43,140
So you mean that time does
that thing that you mentioned.

309
00:15:43,340 --> 00:15:47,070
Well, we do have someone from the future
here, I guess it can't be helped.

310
00:15:47,210 --> 00:15:51,270
Oh no, Miss Asahina
isn't involved in this.

311
00:15:51,380 --> 00:15:52,740
Okay then,
what's the culprit?

312
00:15:52,880 --> 00:15:54,970
I would guess
Miss Suzumiya.

313
00:15:56,780 --> 00:16:00,520
I'm sure she doesn't realize it,
but somewhere inside of her...

314
00:16:00,790 --> 00:16:03,420
is a desire to not let
summer vacation end.

315
00:16:03,560 --> 00:16:06,530
What the heck? Do you mean she
feels regret over something?

316
00:16:06,960 --> 00:16:08,520
That's what I believe.

317
00:16:08,660 --> 00:16:11,630
Perhaps she feels that
there's something left...

318
00:16:11,870 --> 00:16:14,300
that she wants to do
during our summer vacation?

319
00:16:17,240 --> 00:16:19,330
So, what are you saying
I should do?

320
00:16:19,440 --> 00:16:22,810
If we knew that, we would
have this problem solved.

321
00:16:23,310 --> 00:16:25,010
You seem awfully cheerful
about this.

322
00:16:25,680 --> 00:16:28,910
It's because we've finally
been able to solve...

323
